# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bldc-motor-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] In electromechanics, the **counter-electromotive force** (also called **counter EMF**, **CEMF** or **back EMF**), is the opposing electromotive force (EMF) caused by a changing current.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] The changing current leads to a changing magnetic field, and hence induces an EMF in the circuit by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] For example, the voltage appearing across an inductor or coil is due to a change in current which causes a change in the magnetic field within the coil, and therefore the self-induced voltage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] The polarity of the voltage at every moment opposes that of the change in applied voltage, to keep the current constant.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] This effect is not due to the motor's inductance, which generates a voltage in opposition to a changing current via Faraday's law, but a separate phenomenon.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] That is, the back-EMF is also due to inductance and Faraday's law, but occurs even when the motor current is not changing, and arises from the geometric considerations of an armature spinning in a magnetic field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] This voltage is in series with and opposes the original applied voltage and is called "back-electromotive force" (by Lenz's law).
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] With a lower overall voltage across the motor's internal resistance as the motor turns faster, the current flowing into the motor decreases.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] One practical application of this phenomenon is to indirectly measure motor speed and position, as the back-EMF is proportional to the rotational speed of the armature.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] In motor control and robotics, back-EMF often refers most specifically to actually using the voltage generated by a spinning motor to infer the speed of the motor's rotation, for use in better controlling the motor in specific ways.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] To observe the effect of back-EMF of a motor, one can perform this simple exercise: with an incandescent light on, cause a large motor such as a drill press, saw, air conditioner compressor, or vacuum cleaner to start.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] The light may dim briefly as the motor starts.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] When the armature is not turning (called locked rotor) there is no back-EMF and the motor's current draw is quite high.
[src:bldc-motor-control/back-electromotive-force] If the motor's starting current is high enough, it will pull the line voltage down enough to cause noticeable dimming of the light.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A **brushless DC electric motor** (**BLDC**), also known as an **electronically commutated motor**, is a synchronous motor using a direct current (DC) electric power supply.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] It uses an electronic controller to switch DC currents to the motor windings, producing magnetic fields that effectively rotate in space and which the permanent magnet rotor follows.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The controller adjusts the phase and amplitude of the current pulses that control the speed and torque of the motor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] It is an improvement on the mechanical commutator (brushes) used in many conventional electric motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The construction of a brushless motor system is typically similar to a permanent magnet synchronous motor (PMSM), but can also be a switched reluctance motor, or an induction (asynchronous) motor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They may also use neodymium magnets and be outrunners (the stator is surrounded by the rotor), inrunners (the rotor is surrounded by the stator), or axial (the rotor and stator are flat and parallel).
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The advantages of a brushless motor over brushed motors are high power-to-weight ratio, high speed, nearly instantaneous control of speed (rpm) and torque, high efficiency, and low maintenance.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors find applications in such places as computer peripherals (disk drives, printers), hand-held power tools, and vehicles ranging from model aircraft to automobiles.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In modern washing machines, brushless DC motors have allowed replacement of rubber belts and gearboxes by a direct-drive design.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushed DC motors were invented in the 20th century and are still common.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless DC motors were made possible by the development of solid-state electronics in the 1960s.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] An electric motor develops torque by keeping the magnetic fields of the rotor (the rotating part of the machine) and the stator (the fixed part of the machine) misaligned.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] One or both sets of magnets are electromagnets, made of a coil of wire wound around an iron core.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] DC running through the wire winding creates the magnetic field, providing the power that runs the motor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The misalignment generates a torque that tries to realign the fields.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] As the rotor moves and the fields come into alignment, it is necessary to move either the rotor's or stator's field to maintain the misalignment and continue to generate torque and movement.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The device that moves the fields based on the position of the rotor is called a commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In brushed motors, this is done with a rotary switch on the motor's shaft called a commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] It consists of a rotating cylinder or disc divided into multiple metal contact segments on the rotor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The segments are connected to conductor windings on the rotor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Two or more stationary contacts called *brushes*, made of a soft conductor such as graphite, press against the commutator, making sliding electrical contact with successive segments as the rotor turns.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The brushes selectively provide electric current to the windings.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] As the rotor rotates, the commutator selects different windings and the directional current is applied to a given winding such that the rotor's magnetic field remains misaligned with the stator and creates a torque in one direction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The brush commutator has disadvantages that have led to a decline in the use of brushed motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] During the last hundred years, high-power DC brushed motors, once the mainstay of industry, were replaced by alternating current (AC) synchronous motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Today, brushed motors are used only in low-power applications or where only DC is available, but the above drawbacks limit their use even in these applications.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In brushless DC motors, an electronic controller replaces the brush commutator contacts.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The elimination of the sliding contact allows brushless motors to have less friction and longer life; their working life is limited only by the lifetime of their bearings.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushed DC motors develop a maximum torque when stationary, linearly decreasing as velocity increases.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Some limitations of brushed motors can be overcome by brushless motors; they include higher efficiency and lower susceptibility to mechanical wear.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] These benefits come at the cost of potentially less rugged, more complex, and more expensive control electronics.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A typical brushless motor has permanent magnets that rotate around a fixed armature, eliminating problems associated with connecting current to the moving armature.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] An electronic controller replaces the commutator assembly of the brushed DC motor, which continually switches the phase to the windings to keep the motor turning.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The controller performs similar timed power distribution by using a solid-state circuit rather than the commutator system.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] With no windings on the rotor, they are not subjected to centrifugal forces, and because the windings are supported by the housing, they can be cooled by conduction, requiring no airflow inside the motor for cooling.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This, in turn, means that the motor's internals can be entirely enclosed and protected from dirt or other foreign matter.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motor commutation can be implemented in software using a microcontroller, or may alternatively be implemented using analog or digital circuits.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Commutation with electronics instead of brushes allows for greater flexibility and capabilities not available with brushed DC motors, including speed limiting, microstepping operation for slow and fine motion control, and holding torque when stationary.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Controller software can be customized to the specific motor being used in the application, resulting in greater commutation efficiency.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The maximum power that can be applied to a brushless motor is limited almost exclusively by heat; too much heat weakens the magnets and damages the windings' insulation.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] When converting electricity into mechanical power, brushless motors are more efficient than brushed motors primarily due to the absence of brushes, which reduces mechanical energy loss due to friction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The enhanced efficiency is greatest in the no-load and low-load regions of the motor's performance curve.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Environments and requirements in which manufacturers use brushless-type DC motors include maintenance-free operation, high speeds, and operation where sparking is hazardous (i.e., explosive environments) or could affect electronically sensitive equipment.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The construction of a brushless motor resembles a stepper motor, but the motors have important differences in implementation and operation.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] While stepper motors are frequently stopped with the rotor in a defined angular position, a brushless motor is usually intended to produce continuous rotation.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Both motor types may have a rotor position sensor for internal feedback.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Both a stepper motor and a well-designed brushless motor can hold finite torque at zero RPM.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Because the controller implements the traditional brushes' functionality, it needs to know the rotor's orientation relative to the stator coils.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This is automatic in a brushed motor due to the fixed geometry of the rotor shaft and brushes.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Some designs use Hall effect sensors or a rotary encoder to directly measure the rotor's position.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Others measure the back-EMF in the undriven coils to infer the rotor position, eliminating the need for separate Hall effect sensors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] These are therefore often called *sensorless* controllers.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Controllers that sense rotor position based on back-EMF have extra challenges in initiating motion because no back-EMF is produced when the rotor is stationary.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This is usually accomplished by beginning rotation from an arbitrary phase, and then skipping to the correct phase if it is found to be wrong.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This can cause the motor to run backwards briefly, adding even more complexity to the startup sequence.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Other sensorless controllers are capable of measuring winding saturation caused by the position of the magnets to infer the rotor position.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A typical controller contains three polarity-reversible outputs controlled by a logic circuit.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Simple controllers employ comparators working from the orientation sensors to determine when the output phase should be advanced.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] More advanced controllers employ a microcontroller to manage acceleration, control motor speed and fine-tune efficiency.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Two key performance parameters of brushless DC motors are the motor constants $K_{T}$ (torque constant) and $K_{e}$ (back-EMF constant, also known as speed constant $K_{V}={1 \over K_{e}}$ ).
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors can be constructed in several different physical configurations.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the conventional inrunner configuration, the permanent magnets are part of the rotor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Three stator windings surround the rotor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the external-rotor outrunner configuration, the radial relationship between the coils and magnets is reversed; the stator coils form the center (core) of the motor, while the permanent magnets spin within an overhanging rotor that surrounds the core.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Outrunners typically have more poles and have a higher torque at low RPM.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the flat axial flux type, used where there are space or shape constraints, stator and rotor plates are mounted face to face.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In all brushless motors, the coils are stationary.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This is for 3 phase AC motors not DC brushless motors: There are two common electrical winding configurations: the delta configuration connects three windings to each other in a triangle-like circuit, and power is applied at each of the connections.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The wye (*Y*-shaped) configuration, sometimes called a star winding, connects all of the windings to a central point, and power is applied to the remaining end of each winding.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A motor with windings in delta configuration gives low torque at low speed but can give a higher top speed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Wye configuration gives high torque at low speed but not as high top speed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The wye winding is normally more efficient.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Delta-connected windings can allow high-frequency parasitic electrical currents to circulate entirely within the motor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A Wye-connected winding does not contain a closed loop in which parasitic currents can flow, preventing such losses.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Aside from the higher impedance of the wye configuration, from a controller standpoint, the two winding configurations can be treated exactly the same.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors fulfill many functions originally performed by brushed DC motors, but cost and control complexity prevent brushless motors from replacing brushed motors completely in the lowest-cost areas.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Nevertheless, brushless motors have come to dominate many applications, particularly devices such as computer hard drives and CD/DVD players.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Small cooling fans in electronic equipment are powered exclusively by brushless motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They can be found in cordless power tools, where the increased efficiency of the motor leads to longer periods of use before the battery needs to be charged.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Low speed, low power brushless motors are used in direct-drive turntables for gramophone records.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors can also be found in marine applications, such as underwater thrusters.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Drones also utilize brushless motors to elevate their performance.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are found in electric vehicles, hybrid vehicles, personal transporters, and electric aircraft.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Most electric bicycles use brushless motors that are sometimes built into the wheel hub itself, with the stator fixed solidly to the axle and the magnets attached to and rotating with the wheel.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The same principle is applied in self-balancing scooter wheels.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Most electrically powered radio-controlled models use brushless motors because of their high efficiency.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are found in many modern cordless tools, including some string trimmers, leaf blowers, saws (circular and reciprocating), and drills/drivers.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The weight and efficiency advantages of brushless over brushed motors are more important to handheld, battery-powered tools than to large, stationary tools plugged into an AC outlet.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] There is a trend in the heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) and refrigeration industries to use brushless motors instead of various types of AC motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The most significant reason to switch to a brushless motor is a reduction in power required to operate them versus a typical AC motor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In addition to the brushless motor's higher efficiency, HVAC systems, especially those featuring variable-speed or load modulation, use brushless motors to give the built-in microprocessor continuous control over cooling and airflow.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The application of brushless DC motors within industrial engineering primarily focuses on manufacturing engineering or industrial automation design.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are ideally suited for manufacturing applications because of their high power density, good speed-torque characteristics, high efficiency, wide speed ranges and low maintenance.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The most common uses of brushless DC motors in industrial engineering are motion control, linear actuators, servomotors, actuators for industrial robots, extruder drive motors and feed drives for CNC machine tools.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are commonly used as pump, fan and spindle drives in adjustable or variable speed applications as they are capable of developing high torque with good speed response.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In addition, they can be easily automated for remote control.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Due to their construction, they have good thermal characteristics and high energy efficiency.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] To obtain a variable speed response, brushless motors operate in an electromechanical system that includes an electronic motor controller and a rotor position feedback sensor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless DC motors are widely used as servomotors for machine tool servo drives.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Servomotors are used for mechanical displacement, positioning or precision motion control.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] DC stepper motors can also be used as servomotors; however, since they are operated with open loop control, they typically exhibit torque pulsations.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are used in industrial positioning and actuation applications.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] For assembly robots, Brushless technology may be used to build linear motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The advantage of linear motors is that they can produce linear motion without the need of a transmission system, such as ballscrews, leadscrew, rack-and-pinion, cam, gears or belts, that would be necessary for rotary motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Transmission systems are known to introduce less responsiveness and reduced accuracy.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Direct drive, brushless DC linear motors consist of a slotted stator with magnetic teeth and a moving actuator, which has permanent magnets and coil windings.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] To obtain linear motion, a motor controller excites the coil windings in the actuator causing an interaction of the magnetic fields resulting in linear motion.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Tubular linear motors are another form of linear motor design operated in a similar way.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors have become a popular motor choice for model aircraft, including helicopters and drones.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Their favorable power-to-weight ratios and wide range of available sizes have revolutionized the market for electric-powered model flight, displacing virtually all brushed electric motors, except for low powered inexpensive often toy grade aircraft.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They have also encouraged growth of simple, lightweight electric model aircraft, rather than the previous internal combustion engines powering larger and heavier models.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The increased power-to-weight ratio of modern batteries and brushless motors allows models to ascend vertically rather than climb gradually.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The low noise and lack of mass compared to small glow fuel internal combustion engines is another reason for their popularity.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Their popularity has also risen in the radio-controlled car area.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors have been legal in North American RC car racing in accordance with Radio Operated Auto Racing (ROAR) since 2006.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] These motors provide a great amount of power to RC racers and, if paired with appropriate gearing and high-discharge lithium polymer (Li-Po) or lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO4) batteries, these cars can achieve speeds over 160 kilometres per hour (99 mph).
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are capable of producing more torque and have a faster peak rotational speed compared to nitro- or gasoline-powered engines.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Nitro engines peak at around 46,800 r/min and 2.2 kilowatts (3.0 hp), while a smaller brushless motor can reach 50,000 r/min and 3.7 kilowatts (5.0 hp).
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Larger brushless RC motors can reach upwards of 10 kilowatts (13 hp) and 28,000 r/min to power one-fifth-scale models.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are widely used as an alternative to brushed motors in the sport of combat robotics.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They are used in every weight class from 75 grams all the way up to 250 pounds.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] When used for locomotion, brushless motors are often paired with a planetary gearbox in order to decrease the output speed to make the robot more controllable.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Other methods, such as friction drive, achieve the same result using slightly different means.
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are also often used to power kinetic weapons (such as a spinning blade).
[src:bldc-motor-control/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the lower weight classes, weapons are often mounted directly to the motor, while in heavier robots, timing belts, v-belts, and chains are used to transmit power from the motor to the spinning mass.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] A **commutator** is a rotary electrical switch in certain types of electric motors and electrical generators that periodically reverses the current direction between the rotor and the external circuit.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] It consists of a cylinder composed of multiple metal contact segments on the rotating armature of the machine.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Two or more electrical contacts called "brushes" made of a soft conductive material like carbon press against the commutator, making sliding contact with successive segments of the commutator as it rotates.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The windings (coils of wire) on the armature are connected to the commutator segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Commutators are used in direct current (DC) machines: dynamos (DC generators) and many DC motors as well as universal motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In a motor the commutator applies electric current to the windings.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] By reversing the current direction in the rotating windings each half turn, a steady rotating force (torque) is produced.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In a generator the commutator picks off the current generated in the windings, reversing the direction of the current with each half turn, serving as a mechanical rectifier to convert the alternating current from the windings to unidirectional direct current in the external load circuit.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The first direct current commutator-type machine, the dynamo, was built by Hippolyte Pixii in 1832, based on a suggestion by André-Marie Ampère.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Commutators are relatively inefficient, and also require periodic maintenance such as brush replacement.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Therefore, commutated machines are declining in use, being replaced by alternating current (AC) machines, and in recent years by brushless DC motors which use semiconductor switches.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] A commutator consists of a set of contact bars fixed to the rotating shaft of a machine, and connected to the armature windings.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] As the shaft rotates, the commutator reverses the flow of current in a winding.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] For a single armature winding, when the shaft has made one-half complete turn, the winding is now connected so that current flows through it in the opposite of the initial direction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In a motor, the armature current causes the fixed magnetic field to exert a rotational force, or a torque, on the winding to make it turn.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In a generator, the mechanical torque applied to the shaft maintains the motion of the armature winding through the stationary magnetic field, inducing a current in the winding.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In both the motor and generator case, the commutator periodically reverses the direction of current flow through the winding so that current flow in the circuit external to the machine continues in only one direction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Practical commutators have at least three contact segments, to prevent a "dead" spot where two brushes simultaneously bridge only two commutator segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Brushes are made wider than the insulated gap, to ensure that brushes are always in contact with an armature coil.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] For commutators with at least three segments, although the rotor can potentially stop in a position where two commutator segments touch one brush, this only de-energizes one of the rotor arms while the others will still function correctly.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] With the remaining rotor arms, a motor can produce sufficient torque to begin spinning the rotor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] A commutator consists of a set of copper segments, fixed around the part of the circumference of the rotating machine, or the rotor, and a set of spring-loaded brushes fixed to the stationary frame of the machine.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Two or more fixed brushes connect to the external circuit, either a source of current for a motor or a load for a generator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Commutator segments are connected to the coils of the armature, with the number of coils (and commutator segments) depending on the speed and voltage of the machine.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Large motors may have hundreds of segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Each conducting segment of the commutator is insulated from adjacent segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Mica was used on early machines and is still used on large machines.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Many other insulating materials are used to insulate smaller machines; plastics allow quick manufacture of an insulator, for example.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The segments are held onto the shaft using a dovetail shape on the edges or underside of each segment.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Insulating wedges around the perimeter of each segment are pressed so that the commutator maintains its mechanical stability throughout its normal operating range.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In small appliance and tool motors the segments are typically crimped permanently in place and cannot be removed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] When the motor fails it is discarded and replaced.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] On large industrial machines (say, from several kilowatts to thousands of kilowatts in rating) it is economical to replace individual damaged segments, and so the end-wedge can be unscrewed and individual segments removed and replaced.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Replacing the copper and mica segments is commonly referred to as "refilling".
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Disposable, molded type commutators commonly found in smaller DC motors are becoming increasingly more common in larger electric motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Molded type commutators are not repairable and must be replaced if damaged.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Such requirements are common with traction, military, aerospace, nuclear, mining, and high speed applications where clamping failure and segment or insulation protrusion can lead to serious negative consequences.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Friction between the segments and the brushes eventually causes wear to both surfaces.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Carbon brushes, being made of a softer material, wear faster and may be designed to be replaced easily without dismantling the machine.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Older copper brushes caused more wear to the commutator, causing deep grooving and notching of the surface over time.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The commutator on small motors (say, less than a kilowatt rating) is not designed to be repaired through the life of the device.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] On large industrial equipment, the commutator may be re-surfaced with abrasives, or the rotor may be removed from the frame, mounted in a large metal lathe, and the commutator resurfaced by cutting it down to a smaller diameter.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The largest of equipment can include a lathe turning attachment directly over the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Early machines used brushes made from strands of copper wire to contact the surface of the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] However, these hard metal brushes tended to scratch and groove the smooth commutator segments, eventually requiring resurfacing of the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] As the copper brushes wore away, the dust and pieces of the brush could wedge between commutator segments, shorting them and reducing the efficiency of the device.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Fine copper wire mesh or gauze provided better surface contact with less segment wear, but gauze brushes were more expensive than strip or wire copper brushes.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Modern rotating machines with commutators almost exclusively use carbon brushes, which may have copper powder mixed in to improve conductivity.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Metallic copper brushes can be found in toy or very small motors, such as the one illustrated above, and some motors which only operate very intermittently, such as automotive starter motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Motors and generators suffer from a phenomenon known as 'armature reaction', one of the effects of which is to change the position at which the current reversal through the windings should ideally take place as the loading varies.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Early machines had the brushes mounted on a ring that was provided with a handle.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] During operation, it was necessary to adjust the position of the brush ring to adjust the commutation to minimise the sparking at the brushes.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This process was known as 'rocking the brushes'.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Various developments took place to automate the process of adjusting the commutation and minimizing the sparking at the brushes.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] One of these was the development of 'high resistance brushes', or brushes made from a mixture of copper powder and carbon.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Although described as high resistance brushes, the resistance of such a brush was of the order of milliohms, the exact value dependent on the size and function of the machine.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Also, the high resistance brush was not constructed like a brush but in the form of a carbon block with a curved face to match the shape of the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The high resistance or carbon brush is made large enough that it is significantly wider than the insulating segment that it spans (and on large machines may often span two insulating segments).
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The result of this is that as the commutator segment passes from under the brush, the current passing to it ramps down more smoothly than had been the case with pure copper brushes where the contact broke suddenly.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Similarly the segment coming into contact with the brush has a similar ramping up of the current.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Thus, although the current passing through the brush was more or less constant, the instantaneous current passing to the two commutator segments was proportional to the relative area in contact with the brush.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The introduction of the carbon brush had convenient side effects.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Carbon brushes tend to wear more evenly than copper brushes, and the soft carbon causes far less damage to the commutator segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] There is less sparking with carbon as compared to copper, and as the carbon wears away, the higher resistance of carbon results in fewer problems from the dust collecting on the commutator segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The ratio of copper to carbon can be changed for a particular purpose.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Brushes with higher copper content perform better with very low voltages and high current, while brushes with a higher carbon content are better for high voltage and low current.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] High copper content brushes typically carry 150 to 200 amperes per square inch of contact surface, while higher carbon content only carries 40 to 70 amperes per square inch.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The higher resistance of carbon also results in a greater voltage drop of 0.8 to 1.0 volts per contact, or 1.6 to 2.0 volts across the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] A spring is typically used with the brush, to maintain constant contact with the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] As the brush and commutator wear down, the spring steadily pushes the brush downwards towards the commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Eventually the brush wears small and thin enough that steady contact is no longer possible or it is no longer securely held in the brush holder, and so the brush must be replaced.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] It is common for a flexible power cable to be directly attached to the brush, because current flowing through the support spring would cause heating, which may lead to a loss of metal temper and a loss of the spring tension.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] When a commutated motor or generator uses more power than a single brush is capable of conducting, an assembly of several brush holders is mounted in parallel across the surface of the very large commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This parallel holder distributes current evenly across all the brushes, and permits a careful operator to remove a bad brush and replace it with a new one, even as the machine continues to spin fully powered and under load.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] High power, high current commutated equipment is now uncommon, due to the less complex design of alternating current generators that permits a low current, high voltage spinning field coil to energize high current fixed-position stator coils.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This permits the use of very small singular brushes in the alternator design.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In this instance, the rotating contacts are continuous rings, called slip rings, and no switching happens.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Modern devices using carbon brushes usually have a maintenance-free design that requires no adjustment throughout the life of the device, using a fixed-position brush holder slot and a combined brush-spring-cable assembly that fits into the slot.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The worn brush is pulled out and a new brush inserted.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The different brush types make contact with the commutator in different ways.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Because copper brushes have the same hardness as the commutator segments, the rotor cannot be spun backwards against the ends of copper brushes without the copper digging into the segments and causing severe damage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Consequently, strip/laminate copper brushes only make tangential contact with the commutator, while copper mesh and wire brushes use an inclined contact angle touching their edge across the segments of a commutator that can spin in only one direction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The softness of carbon brushes permits direct radial end-contact with the commutator without damage to the segments, permitting easy reversal of rotor direction, without the need to reorient the brush holders for operation in the opposite direction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Although never reversed, common appliance motors that use wound rotors, commutators and brushes have radial-contact brushes.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In the case of a reaction-type carbon brush holder, carbon brushes may be reversely inclined with the commutator so that the commutator tends to push against the carbon for firm contact.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The contact point where a brush touches the commutator is referred to as the *commutating plane*.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] To conduct sufficient current to or from the commutator, the brush contact area is not a thin line but instead a rectangular patch across the segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Typically the brush is wide enough to span 2.5 commutator segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This means that two adjacent segments are electrically connected by the brush when it contacts both.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Most introductions to motor and generator design start with a simple two-pole device with the brushes arranged at a perfect 90-degree angle from the field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This ideal is useful as a starting point for understanding how the fields interact but it is not how a motor or generator functions in actual practice.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In a real motor or generator, the field around the rotor is never perfectly uniform.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Instead, the rotation of the rotor induces field effects which drag and distort the magnetic lines of the outer non-rotating stator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The faster the rotor spins, the further this degree of field distortion.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Because a motor or generator operates most efficiently with the rotor field at right angles to the stator field, it is necessary to either retard or advance the brush position to put the rotor's field into the correct position to be at a right angle to the distorted field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] These field effects are reversed when the direction of spin is reversed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] It is therefore difficult to build an efficient reversible commutated dynamo, since for highest field strength it is necessary to move the brushes to the opposite side of the normal neutral plane.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] These effects can be mitigated by a compensation winding in the face of the field pole that carries armature current.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The effect can be considered to be analogous to timing advance in an internal combustion engine.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Generally a dynamo that has been designed to run at a certain fixed speed will have its brushes permanently fixed to align the field for highest efficiency at that speed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Self-induction – The magnetic fields in each coil of wire join and compound together to create a magnetic field that resists changes in the current, which can be likened to the current having inertia.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In the coils of the rotor, even after the brush has been reached, currents tend to continue to flow for a brief moment, resulting in a wasted energy as heat due to the brush spanning across several commutator segments and the current short-circuiting across the segments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] To minimize sparking at the brushes due to this short-circuiting, the brushes are advanced a few degrees further yet, beyond the advance for field distortions.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This moves the rotor winding undergoing commutation slightly forward into the stator field which has magnetic lines in the opposite direction and which oppose the field in the stator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This opposing field helps to reverse the lagging self-inducting current in the stator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] So even for a rotor which is at rest and initially requires no compensation for spinning field distortions, the brushes should still be advanced beyond the perfect 90-degree angle as taught in so many beginners textbooks, to compensate for self-induction.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Modern motor and generator devices with commutators are able to counteract armature reaction through the use of *interpoles*, which are small field coils and pole pieces positioned approximately halfway between the primary poles of the stator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] By applying a dynamic varying field to the interpoles as the load, RPM, or direction of rotation of the device changes, it is possible to balance out field distortions from armature reaction so that the brush position can remain fixed and sparking across the segments is minimized.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Although direct current motors and dynamos once dominated industry, the disadvantages of the commutator have caused a decline in the use of commutated machines in the last century.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] With the wide availability of alternating current, DC motors have been replaced by more efficient AC synchronous or induction motors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In recent years, with the widespread availability of power semiconductors, in many remaining applications commutated DC motors have been replaced with "brushless direct current motors".
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] These don't have a commutator; instead the direction of the current is switched electronically.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] A sensor keeps track of the rotor position and semiconductor switches such as transistors reverse the current.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Operating life of these machines is much longer, limited mainly by bearing wear.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] These are single-phase AC-only motors with higher starting torque than could be obtained with split-phase starting windings, before high-capacitance (non-polar, relatively high-current electrolytic) starting capacitors became practical.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] They have a conventional wound stator as with any induction motor, but the wire-wound rotor is much like that with a conventional commutator.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Brushes opposite each other are connected to each other (not to an external circuit), and transformer action induces currents into the rotor that develop torque by repulsion.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] One variety, notable for having an adjustable speed, runs continuously with brushes in contact, while another uses repulsion only for high starting torque and in some cases lifts the brushes once the motor is running fast enough.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] In the latter case, all commutator segments are connected together as well, before the motor attains running speed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Once at speed, the rotor windings become functionally equivalent to the squirrel-cage structure of a conventional induction motor, and the motor runs as such.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Commutators were used as simple forward-off-reverse switches for electrical experiments in physics laboratories.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This is similar in design to the commutators used in motors and dynamos.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] It was usually constructed of brass and ivory (later ebonite).
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] This consists of a block of wood or ebonite with four wells, containing mercury, which are cross connected by copper wires.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] The output is taken from a pair of curved copper wires which are moved to dip into one or other pair of mercury wells.
[src:bldc-motor-control/commutator-electric] Instead of mercury, ionic liquids or other liquid metals such as galinstan can be used.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A **Hall effect sensor** (also known as a **Hall sensor** or **Hall probe**) is any sensor based on the *Hall effect* (named after physicist Edwin Hall), in which a voltage is produced proportional to one axial component of the magnetic field vector **B**.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are used for proximity sensing, positioning, speed detection, and current sensing applications and are common in industrial and consumer applications.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hundreds of millions of Hall sensor integrated circuits (ICs) are sold each year by about 50 manufacturers, with the global market being valued at around a billion dollars.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] In a Hall sensor, a fixed DC bias current is applied along one axis across a thin strip of metal called the Hall element transducer.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Sensing electrodes on opposite sides of the Hall element along *another* axis measure the difference in electric potential (voltage) across the axis of the electrodes.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The current's charge carriers are deflected by the Lorentz force in the presence of a magnetic field perpendicular to their flow.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The sensing electrodes measure the potential difference (the Hall voltage) proportional to the axial component of the magnetic field that is perpendicular to *both* the current's axis and the sensing electrodes' axis.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect sensors respond both to static magnetic fields and to changing ones.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The Hall voltage is also temperature-dependent and can have an offset.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Due to the proportionality of the Hall voltage to the charge carrier mobility and the concentration of the majority charge carriers, the Hall effect is an established method for determining these parameters in semiconductor technology.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect devices produce a very low signal level and thus require amplification.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The vacuum tube amplifier technology available in the first half of the 20th century was too large, expensive, and power-consuming for everyday Hall effect sensor applications, which were limited to laboratory instruments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Even early generation transistor technology was unsuited; it was only with the development of the low-cost silicon chip-based integrated circuit (IC) micro-technology that the Hall effect sensor became suitable for mass application.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Devices sold as Hall sensors nowadays contain both the sensor as described above and a high gain IC amplifier in a single package.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] These Hall sensor ICs may add a stable voltage regulator in addition to the amplifier to allow operation over a wide range of supply voltage and boost the Hall voltage for a convenient analog signal output proportional to the magnetic field component.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] In some cases, the linear circuit may cancel the offset voltage of Hall sensors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Moreover, AC modulation of the driving current may also reduce the influence of this offset voltage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are called *linear* if their output is proportional to the incident magnetic field strength.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This output signal can be an analog voltage, a pulse-width modulation (PWM) signal, or be communicated digitally over a modern bus protocol.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors may also be *ratiometric* if their sensitivity is also proportional to their supply voltage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] With no magnetic field applied, their *quiescent output voltage* is typically half of the supply voltage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] While the Hall element is an analog device, *Hall switch* ICs often additionally incorporate threshold detection circuitry to form an electronic switch which has two states (on and off) that output a binary digital signal.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Their outputs may be open collector NPN transistors (or open drain n-type MOSFETs) for compatibility with ICs that use different supply voltages.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Rather than a voltage being produced at the Hall sensor signal output wire, an output transistor is turned on, providing a circuit to ground through the signal output wire.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Schmitt trigger filtering may be applied (or integrated into the IC) to provide a clean digital output that is robust against sensor noise.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The hysteresis thresholds for switching (specified as BOP and BRP) categorize digital Hall ICs as either unipolar switches, omnipolar switches, or bipolar switches, which may sometimes be called latches.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Unipolar (e.g., A3144) refers to having switching thresholds in only one polarity of the magnetic field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Omnipolar switches have two sets of switching thresholds, for both positive and negative polarities, and so operate alternatively with a strong positive or a strong negative magnetic field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Bipolar switches have a positive BOP and a negative BRP (and thus require both positive and negative magnetic fields to operate).
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The difference between BOP and BRP tends to be greater for bipolar switches described as latches, which remain in one state much longer (i.e. they latch onto their last value) and require a greater field strength to change states than bipolar switches require.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The naming distinction between "bipolar" and "latch" may be a little arbitrary, for instance, the datasheet for the Honeywell SS41F describes it as "bipolar", while another manufacturer describes their SS41F with comparable specifications as a "latch".
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall elements measure only the sensing axis component of the magnetic field vector.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Because that axial component may be positive or negative, some Hall sensors can sense the binary direction of the axial component in addition to its magnitude.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] An additional perpendicularly-oriented Hall element (e.g. in § Dual Hall sensor ICs) must be incorporated to determine a 2-D direction, and another perpendicularly-oriented Hall element must be added to detect the full 3-D components of the magnetic field vector.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Because Hall sensor ICs are solid-state devices, they are not prone to mechanical wear.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Thus, they can operate at much higher speeds than mechanical sensors, and their lifespan is not limited by mechanical failure (unlike potentiometers, electromechanical reed switches, relays, or other mechanical switches and sensors).
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] However, Hall sensors can be prone to thermal drift due to changes in environmental conditions and to time drift over the lifetime of the sensor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect devices (when appropriately packaged) are immune to dust, dirt, mud, and water.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] These characteristics make Hall effect devices better for position sensing than alternative means such as optical and electromechanical sensing.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The bandwidth of practical Hall sensors is limited to the hundreds of kilohertz, with commercial silicon ones commonly limited to 10–100 kHz.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] As of 2016, the fastest Hall sensor available in the market has a bandwidth of 1 MHz but uses non-standard semiconductors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Magnetic flux from the surroundings (such as other wires) may diminish or enhance the field the Hall probe intends to detect, rendering the results inaccurate.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors can detect stray magnetic fields easily, including that of Earth, so they work well as electronic compasses: but this also means that such stray fields can hinder accurate measurements of small magnetic fields.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] To solve this problem, Hall sensors are often integrated with magnetic shielding of some kind.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Mechanical positions within an electromagnetic system can instead be measured without the Hall effect using optical position encoders (e.g., absolute and incremental encoders) and induced voltage by moving the amount of metalcore inserted into a transformer.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] When Hall is compared to photo-sensitive methods, it is harder to get an absolute position with Hall.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] While a single Hall element is susceptible to external magnetic fields, a differential configuration of two Hall elements can cancel stray fields out from measurements, analogous to how common mode voltage signals are canceled using differential signaling.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect sensors may be used in various sensors such as rotating speed sensors (bicycle wheels, gear-teeth, automotive speedometers, electronic ignition systems), fluid flow sensors, current sensors, and pressure sensors.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are commonly used to time the speed of wheels and shafts (see Figure 1), such as for internal combustion engine ignition timing, tachometers and anti-lock braking systems.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Common applications are often found where a robust and contactless alternative to a mechanical switch or potentiometer is required.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] These include: electric airsoft guns, triggers of electropneumatic paintball guns, go-kart speed controls, smartphones, and some global positioning systems.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] One of the most common industrial applications of Hall sensors used as binary switches is in position sensing (see Figure 2).
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect sensors are used to detect whether a smartphone's cover (that includes a small magnet) is closed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Some computer printers use Hall sensors to detect missing paper and open covers and some 3D printers use them to measure filament thickness.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are used in some automotive fuel-level indicators by detecting the position of a floating element in the fuel tank.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors affixed to mechanical gauges that have magnetized indicator needles can translate the physical position or orientation of the mechanical indicator needle into an electrical signal that can be used by electronic indicators, controls, or communications devices.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect magnetometers (also called tesla meters or gauss meters) use a "Hall probe", with a Hall element, to measure magnetic fields or inspect materials (such as tubing or pipelines) using the principles of magnetic flux leakage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A Hall probe is a device that uses a calibrated Hall-effect sensor to directly measure the strength of a magnetic field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Since magnetic fields have a direction as well as a magnitude, the results from a Hall probe are dependent on the orientation, as well as the position, of the probe.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors may be utilized for contactless measurements of direct current in current transformers.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] In such a case the Hall sensor is mounted in a gap in the magnetic core around the current conductor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] As a result, the DC magnetic flux can be measured, and the DC in the conductor can be calculated.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] When electrons flow through a conductor, a magnetic field is produced.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Thus, it is possible to create a non-contacting current sensor or ammeters.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A sensor voltage is applied across two terminals and the third provides a voltage proportional to the current being sensed.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This has several advantages; no additional resistance (a *shunt*, required for the most common current sensing method) needs to be inserted in the primary circuit.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Also, the voltage present on the line to be sensed is not transmitted to the sensor, which enhances the safety of measuring equipment.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This configuration also provides an improvement in signal-to-noise ratio and drift effects of over 20 times that of a bare Hall device.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The range of a given feedthrough sensor may also be extended upward and downward by appropriate wiring.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] To extend the range to lower currents, multiple turns of the current-carrying wire may be made through the opening, each turn adding to the sensor output the same quantity; when the sensor is installed onto a printed circuit board, the turns can be carried out by a staple on the board.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] To extend the range to higher currents, a current divider may be used.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The divider splits the current across two wires of differing widths and the thinner wire, carrying a smaller proportion of the total current, passes through the sensor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A variation on the ring sensor uses a split sensor that is clamped onto the line enabling the device to be used in temporary test equipment.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] If used in a permanent installation, a split sensor allows the electric current to be tested without dismantling the existing circuit.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The output is proportional to both the applied magnetic field and the applied sensor voltage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] If the magnetic field is applied by a solenoid, the sensor output is proportional to the product of the current through the solenoid and the sensor voltage.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] As most applications requiring computation are now performed by small digital computers, the remaining useful application is in power sensing, which combines current sensing with voltage sensing in a single Hall effect device.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] By sensing the current provided to a load, and using the device's applied voltage as a sensor voltage, it is possible to determine the power dissipated by a device, to implement a wattmeter.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect devices used in motion sensing and motion limit switches can offer enhanced reliability in extreme environments.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] As there are no moving parts involved within the sensor or magnet, typical life expectancy is improved compared to traditional electromechanical switches.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Additionally, the sensor and magnet may be encapsulated in an appropriate protective material.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Commonly used in distributors for ignition timing (and in some types of crank- and camshaft-position sensors for injection pulse timing, speed sensing, etc.) the Hall effect sensor is used as a direct replacement for the mechanical breaker points used in earlier automotive applications.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Its use as an ignition timing device in various distributor types is as follows: a stationary permanent magnet and semiconductor Hall effect chip are mounted next to each other separated by an air gap, forming the Hall effect sensor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A metal rotor consisting of windows or tabs is mounted on a shaft and arranged so that, during shaft rotation, the windows or tabs pass through the air gap between the permanent magnet and semiconductor Hall chip.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This effectively shields and exposes the Hall chip to the permanent magnet's field respective of whether a tab or window is passing through the Hall sensor.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] For ignition timing purposes, the metal rotor will have several equal-sized windows or tabs matching the number of engine cylinders (the #1 cylinder tab will always be unique, for discernment by the Engine Control Unit).
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This produces a uniform output similar to a square wave, since the shielding and exposure time are equal.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This signal is used by the engine computer or ECU to control ignition timing.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The sensing of wheel rotation is especially useful in anti-lock braking systems.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The principles of such systems have been extended and refined to offer more than anti-skid functions, now providing extended vehicle-handling enhancements.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Some types of brushless DC electric motors use Hall effect sensors to detect the position of the rotor and feed that information to the motor controller.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This allows for more precise motor control.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors in 3 or 4-pin brushless DC motors sense the position of the rotor and facilitate switching the transistors in the right sequence.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A Hall-effect thruster (HET) is a device that is used to propel some spacecraft, after the spacecraft gets into orbit or farther out into space.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] In the HET, atoms are ionized and accelerated by an electric field.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A radial magnetic field established by magnets on the thruster is used to trap electrons which then orbit and create an electric field due to the Hall effect.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] A large potential is established between the end of the thruster where neutral propellant is fed, and the part where electrons are produced; so, electrons trapped in the magnetic field cannot drop to the lower potential.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] They are thus extremely energetic, which means that they can ionize neutral atoms.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Neutral propellant is pumped into the chamber and is ionized by the trapped electrons.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Positive ions and electrons are then ejected from the thruster as a quasineutral plasma, creating thrust.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The thrust produced is extremely small, with a very low mass flow rate and a very high effective exhaust velocity/specific impulse.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This is achieved at the cost of very high electrical power requirements, on the order of tens of kW per Newton of thrust.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensor ICs often integrate digital electronics.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This enables advanced corrections to the sensor characteristics (e.g. temperature-coefficient corrections), digital communication to microprocessor systems, and may provide interfaces for input diagnostics, fault protection for transient conditions, and short/open-circuit detection.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Some Hall sensor ICs include DSP, which can allow for more processing techniques directly within the sensor package.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Some Hall sensor ICs integrate an analog-to-digital converter and an I2C (Inter-integrated circuit communication protocol) IC for direct connection to a microcontroller's I/O port.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The ESP32 microcontroller even has an integrated Hall sensor that hypothetically could be read by the microcontroller's internal analog-to-digital converter, though it does not work.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors normally require at least three pins (for power, ground, and output).
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] However, two-wire ICs only use a power and ground pin, and instead communicate data using different current levels.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Multiple two-wire ICs may operate from a single supply line, to further reduce wiring.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall-effect switches for computer keyboards were developed in the late 1960s by Everett A.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Due to high manufacturing costs these keyboards were often reserved for high-reliability applications such as in aerospace and the military.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] As mass-production costs have declined, an increasing number of consumer models have become available.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Hall-effect sensors can also be found on some high-performance gaming keyboards (made by companies such as SteelSeries, Wooting, Corsair), with the switches themselves containing magnets.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Applications for Hall effect sensing have also expanded to industrial applications, which now use Hall effect joysticks to control hydraulic valves, replacing the traditional mechanical levers with contactless sensing.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Such applications include mining trucks, backhoe loaders, cranes, diggers, scissor lifts, etc.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] This is useful for counting a series of increments (an incremental encoder) to make a linear or rotary encoder, whereby a moving or rotating arrangement of magnets produces an alternating magnetic pattern sensed as a quadrature encoded pattern.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] That pattern can then be decoded to provide both the speed and direction of movement or simply counted up and down to determine the position or angle.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] (When only one Hall element is used, the direction of linear or rotary encoders cannot be determined).
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] The two elements placed at a precise distance apart from each other on the die may be oriented in the same direction, in which case the magnetic pole-to-pole pitch should ideally be two times the Hall element-to-element pitch.
[src:bldc-motor-control/hall-effect-sensor] Alternatively, the Hall elements may be oriented at 90 degrees to provide sensing in two axes.
